# Two rendering pipelines, one source format

Authors write fenced code blocks tagged with language `mermaid`. Two
pipelines consume them; never introduce a third without updating this rule:

- **Chat view** â€” `prepareMarkdownHtml` produces a pre-rendered HTML string
  (unchanged). `MessageMarkdown` uses `html-react-parser` to walk that
  string and replace every `<pre><code class="language-mermaid">` subtree
  with a `<MermaidBlock>` React component. `MermaidBlock` owns the async
  `mermaid.parse` + `mermaid.render` sequence (see "Parse before render"
  below), the diagram/source toggle, and the error fallback.
  `useMermaid` (called once in `MessageMarkdown`) bootstraps the mermaid
  singleton with `startOnLoad: false` and keeps the theme in sync with
  `ThemeModeContext`.

- **HTML export** â€” `cursor_view/export/mermaid.py::transform_mermaid_fences_to_html`
  rewrites mermaid fences to `<div class="mermaid">` blocks before
  Python-Markdown sees them. `load_vendored_mermaid_js` + `build_mermaid_init_script`
  inject the vendored bundle and an initializer tag before `</body>` so
  every exported file is self-contained (no network at view time).

# BLOBs stay out of the cache

Rendered mermaid SVGs are **not** image attachments and must not land in
`chat_image`, `chat_message`, `chat_search_text`, `chat_search_fts`, or
any source-row hash input. See [`image-attachments.mdc`](image-attachments.mdc)
and [`sqlite-cursor-db.mdc`](sqlite-cursor-db.mdc).

# Theme sync

- `MermaidBlock` reads `darkMode` from `ThemeModeContext` and re-renders
  when it flips. `mermaid.initialize` is called with
  `theme: darkMode ? 'dark' : 'default'` immediately before each
  `mermaid.render` call.
- `build_mermaid_init_script(theme_mode)` maps `"dark"` â†’ `"dark"`,
  everything else â†’ `"default"`, matching the `EXPORT_HTML_THEMES` palette
  logic in `cursor_view/export/themes.py`.
- The mermaid theme must never be hard-coded; it must always be derived from
  the same `theme_mode` / `darkMode` source that drives the surrounding UI.

# Parse before render

Both rendering pipelines that call `mermaid.render` must call
`mermaid.parse` on the same source first and skip `mermaid.render`
entirely when parse rejects. `mermaid.render` injects a "bomb" SVG
element directly into `document.body` as a side effect when its internal
parse fails, and that DOM mutation cannot be undone from the `.catch`
handler. Without the guard, every dark/light toggle on a chat that
contains an invalid diagram re-runs the failing render and leaves one
more orphaned bomb at the end of the page (the original symptom that
motivated the invariant â€” see the entry in
[`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc)). `mermaid.parse` is DOM-free; it
throws on invalid syntax without touching `document.body`, which is what
makes parse-first safe to run on every theme flip.

The two parse-first sites:

- `frontend/src/components/MermaidBlock.js` â€” the per-block render
  effect awaits `mermaid.parse(source)` first, surfaces the parse error
  through the same source-fallback UI as a render-time error, and only
  allocates a render id and calls `mermaid.render` when parse succeeded.
  Theme flips re-run the effect, so the guard fires on every toggle,
  not just first mount.
- `frontend/src/utils/prerenderMermaidDiagrams.js` â€” the pre-paint pass
  awaits `mermaid.parse(source)` before `mermaid.render` for the same
  reason; this keeps the bomb out of `document.body` while the chat is
  still loading, before any `MermaidBlock` mounts.

A future third pipeline (per "Two rendering pipelines, one source
format") must adopt the same parse-first sequence.

# Theme-tagged prerender entries

`prerenderMermaidDiagrams` returns a Map whose values have the shape
`{ svg, error, darkMode }`. The third field carries the `darkMode`
value the entry was rendered against and exists so `MermaidBlock` can
detect a theme shift between prerender and mount. `MessageMarkdown`'s
`replaceNode` interceptor forwards each entry's `darkMode` to its
matching `MermaidBlock` as the `initialDarkMode` prop alongside
`initialSvg` and `initialError`; do not strip this field, and do not
introduce a third Map shape.

`MermaidBlock`'s `skipFirstRenderRef` may suppress the first-mount
render only when the prerender result is still authoritative for the
current theme:

- An `initialError` entry qualifies unconditionally: the parse error
  message is theme-independent and the source-fallback UI is the same
  in both themes.
- An `initialSvg` entry qualifies only when `initialDarkMode === darkMode`
  in `MermaidBlock`'s render context. A mismatch means the user toggled
  theme during `ChatDetail`'s loading window, the cached SVG was themed
  against the prior value, and the per-block effect must run on first
  mount so the diagram is re-themed.
- The no-prerender-data case (`initialSvg`, `initialError`, and
  `initialDarkMode` all `undefined`) cleanly degrades to "do not skip"
  because the boolean expression `Boolean(initialError) ||
  (Boolean(initialSvg) && initialDarkMode === darkMode)` is `false`.

This rule exists to close the chat-detail prerender-vs-toggle race
documented in [`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc): without the theme
match check, `skipFirstRenderRef` would suppress the very render that
would correct a theme-mismatched cached SVG, leaving valid diagrams
stuck in the prerender's theme until something else re-triggered the
per-block effect. The fix lives in the consumer (`MermaidBlock`)
rather than in the producer (`ChatDetail`'s fetch effect) because
adding `darkMode` to the fetch effect deps would refetch the chat over
the network on every theme toggle, which is a worse UX trade than the
sub-frame async-render window the consumer-side fix produces.

# Graceful source fallback on parse error

When `mermaid.parse` rejects (the dominant case, gated by the
parse-before-render section above) or `mermaid.render` rejects (the
post-parse backstop), `MermaidBlock` surfaces the error message via a
`<Typography color="error">` caption and forces `mode = 'source'` so the
raw fence text is always visible. This is deliberate graceful
degradation â€” not a [`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc) `TODO(bug):`.
Do not silently swallow parse errors or render a blank box.

# Escape before inlining (HTML export)

`transform_mermaid_fences_to_html` runs `html.escape` on the mermaid body
before wrapping it in `<div class="mermaid">`. This is the actual XSS
boundary for authored content. Mermaid's `securityLevel: "strict"` is
belt-and-braces on top; removing the `html.escape` call is not safe even
if `securityLevel` is set.

# Markdown and JSON exports leave fences verbatim

`cursor_view/export/markdown.py` emits message content unchanged.
`mermaid`-tagged fences render on any GitHub-flavored markdown viewer
without any transformation from us. Do not add diagram rendering to the
Markdown or JSON export paths.

# Vendored mermaid.min.js

The UMD browser build lives at `cursor_view/export/vendor/mermaid.min.js`
and is committed to the repo. It is **not** a generated build artifact of
this project; it is a vendored third-party asset, analogous to a
`third_party/` or `vendor/` directory in other projects.

`cursor_view/export/vendor/` is the **only** place vendored third-party
JS/CSS assets may live. Do not add a second `vendor/` dir elsewhere.

## Update procedure

When bumping the mermaid version:

1. Update `"mermaid"` in `frontend/package.json` and run `npm install`
   inside `frontend/`.
2. Copy `frontend/node_modules/mermaid/dist/mermaid.min.js` to
   `cursor_view/export/vendor/mermaid.min.js`.
3. Overwrite `cursor_view/export/vendor/VERSION.txt` with the new version
   string (no trailing newline).
4. Commit all three files together.

The frontend (`mermaid` npm package) and the export (`mermaid.min.js`) must
track the **same major version** to avoid diagram-syntax drift between the
chat view and HTML exports.

# Prose references to mermaid fence syntax

When writing plan files, rules, or other documentation that needs to mention
the literal text of a mermaid opening fence, do **not** use a 4-backtick
inline-code span to wrap it. Cursor's chat renderer treats the inner triple
backticks as an opening fence and produces a parse error. Use phrasing such
as "a fenced code block tagged with language `mermaid`" instead.
